 6 December 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924081205/http://www.premier.sa.gov.au/images/news_releases/14_08August/birdsanctuary.pdf |archive-date= 24 September 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\nThe SA Government has also committed to an expenditure of A$1.7 million over a period of four years for the sanctuary's establishment and its ongoing maintenance, with a likely completion in 2018.<ref name=hunter/><ref name= NRAMLR-Dec14>{{cite web|title= International Bird Sanctuary takes flight |url= http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/adelaidemtloftyranges/plants-and-animals/adelaide-bird-sanctuary |publisher=Department of Environment Water and Natural Resources, Natural Resources Adelaide and Mt Lofty Ranges (NRAMLR)|date=|page= |accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nLand in the localities of [[Windsor, South Australia|Windsor]], [[Dublin, South Australia|Dublin]] and [[Lower Light, South Australia|Lower Light]] was proclaimed as a national park under the ''National Parks and Wildlife Act 1972'' on 27 October 2016 with the name ''Adelaide International Bird Sanctuary National Park\u2014Winaityinaityi Pangkara'' with ''Winaityinaityi Pangkara'' being the national park's name in the [[Kaurna language|language]] of the [[Kaurna]] people, whose traditional lands include the Adelaide metropolitan area and the extent of the national park.<ref name=LMV/><ref name=SAGG>{{cite web|title=National Parks and Wildlife (Adelaide International Bird Sanctuary National Park\u2014Winaityinaityi Pangkara\u2014Mining Rights) Proclamation 2016 |url=http://www.governmentgazette.sa.gov.au/sites/default/files/documentstore/2016/October/2016_069.pdf |work=South Australian Government Gazette|publisher=Government of South Australia|pages=4240\u20134243 |accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=ABC>{{cite web|title=Migratory bird haven near Adelaide declared national park |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-10-28/international-bird-sanctuary-national-park-adelaide/7976122