{"title_page": "Chorlton High School", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n| name         = Chorlton High School\n| image        = \n| image_size         = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.4365|-2.2649|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        = \n| established  = 1924\n| type         = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation     = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = Ms Z.  Morris<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cdn.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/sites/default/files/letters/Letter%20to%20parents%20-%20Y6.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425063244/http://cdn.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/sites/default/files/letters/Letter%20to%20parents%20-%20Y6.pdf |archive-date=25 April 2016 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| chair_label  = \n| chair        =\n| founder      = \n| address       = Nell Lane\n| city         = [[Manchester]]\n| county       = \n| country      = England\n| postcode     = M21 7SL\n| ofsted       = yes\n| dfeno        = 352/4281\n| urn          = 139148\n| staff        =\n| enrolment   = 1490~\n| gender       = [[Mixed-sex education|Coeducational]]\n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 16\n| houses       = \n| colours      =\n| publication  =\n| free_label_1 = Executive headteacher\n| free_1       = Mr A Park\n| free_label_2 =\n| free_2       =\n| free_label_3 =\n| free_3       =\n| website      = http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/\n}}\n'''Chorlton High School''' is a [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] secondary school with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], located in [[Chorlton-cum-Hardy]], Manchester, England. It has around 1500 pupils and 300 in each year.\n\n== History ==\n===Grammar school===\nChorlton Grammar School for Boys<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.manchester.gov.uk/Display.php?irn=61138&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&session=pass&QueryName=BasicQuery&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&Anywhere=SummaryData%7CAdmWebMetadata&QueryTerms=chorlton+school&QueryOption=Anywhere&StartAt=41&TestCookie=Test&__utmc=92605445&__utma=92605445.1656834395.1362681656.1362681656.1362681656.1&__utmz=92605445.1362681656.1.1.utmcsr%3Dmanchester.gov.uk%7Cutmccn%3D%28referral%29%7Cutmcmd%3Dreferral%7Cutmcct%3D%2Fa_to_z%2Fservice%2F1744%2Fimages_of_manchester&EMUSESSID=a3a5fefc82ca5a289274efa7f5a4a4cc|title=Chorlton Grammar School for Boys, Corkland Road, Chorlton-cum-Hardy, Manchester, 1927 |year=2010|work=Local Image Collection|publisher=Manchester City Council|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref> was founded in September 1924 with 110 boys due to the growing need to educate older local boys.<ref>An earlier school in Chorlton (founded) 1872) was renamed Chorlton High Schools in 1874; there was a Chorlton Grammar School in High Lane, 1896\u20131930. Lloyd, John (1972) ''The Township of Chorlton-cum-Hardy''. Manchester: E. J. Morten; pp. 98\u201399</ref> The first headmaster was A. F. Chappell, appointed in 1925. During Second World War it was twice evacuated to [[Fleetwood]], owing to the [[Manchester Blitz|Blitz]]; school records for the period during the war are sketchy, as the boys were moved around multiple times. The first headmaster retired in 1951 and was succeeded by Mr Merriman a year later. In 1952 it became a grammar school as pupil numbers started increasing again. The third and final headmaster was C. A. Crofts, appointed in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgsob.co.uk/cgsob/phpBB2/images/cgs/johnford/history.pdf|title=A Potted History|website=Cgsob.co.uk|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> There was at one time a lower school in Darley Avenue (formerly Barlow Hall School).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.manchester.gov.uk/Display.php?irn=64845&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&session=pass&QueryName=BasicQuery&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&Anywhere=SummaryData%7CAdmWebMetadata&QueryTerms=chorlton+school&QueryOption=Anywhere&StartAt=61&TestCookie=Test&__utmc=92605445&__utma=92605445.1656834395.1362681656.1362681656.1362698224.2&__utmz=92605445.1362681656.1.1.utmcsr%3Dmanchester.gov.uk%7Cutmccn%3D%28referral%29%7Cutmcmd%3Dreferral%7Cutmcct%3D%2Fa_to_z%2Fservice%2F1744%2Fimages_of_manchester&EMUSESSID=a3a5fefc82ca5a289274efa7f5a4a4cc&__utmb=92605445.2.10.1362698224|title=Chorlton High School, Darley Avenue (lower school), later Oakwood High School, lower school, Chorlton-cum-Hardy, Manchester, 1975|year=2010|work=Local Image Collection|publisher=Manchester City Council|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Comprehensive===\nDuring the 1960s it returned to its comprehensive roots. The existing building of Chorlton High School at Nell Lane (built in the early 1960s) replaced the old school at Sandy Lane (Corkland Road), which was formerly Chorlton Grammar School; in the early years it was called Oakwood High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.axcis.co.uk/schools-directory/Oakwood-High-School/34515|title=Oakwood High School|publisher=AXCIS Education Recruitment|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgsob.co.uk/cgsob/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=315|title=High school to Grammar school|last=Bancroft|first=Tom|date=2007\u20132010|work=Chorlton Grammar School Old Boys|accessdate=8 March 2013|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Chorlton Grammar School on Corkland Road merged with Barlow Hall Secondary Modern School in 1967, when all of Manchester's secondary state schools became comprehensive. Oakwood High School was the name give to the school, formed by the amalgamation of Wilbraham High School and Chorlton High School in the early 1980s. The current site of Chorlton High School at Nell Lane, was the original site of the Wilbraham High School Upper School.<ref>[https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/ever-present-head-retires-996026]{{cite news|title= Ever-present Head Retires Manchester Evening News, 27 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nIt was designated a specialist [[Arts College]] in 2002.<ref>[http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/artcollege_main.shtml Arts College] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129074052/http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/artcollege_main.shtml |date=29 January 2013 }}</ref> In May 2012, the school governors approved the controversial decision to convert into an [[Academy (England)|academy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Parents' anger over Chorlton High School academy 'whitewash'|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/parents-anger-over-chorlton-high-688824|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> The school became an academy on 1 January 2013.\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\nDue to the [[2020 coronavirus outbreak in the United Kingdom]], the school, along with all of the schools in the UK, was shut in March 2020 until further notice, leaving students into home learning.\n\n== Notable people ==\nA recording studio commemorates [[Maurice Gibb]], though none of the [[Bee Gees]] studied at Chorlton High School. They went to the nearby Oswald Road primary school but the family then emigrated to Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3705559.stm|title=Bee Gees go back to their roots|date=12 May 2004|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Chorlton High School ===\n* [[Tosin Adarabioyo]], footballer for Manchester City{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2020}}\n* [[U.S.G.|Geko]], rapper{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Trevor Davey]], Member of Parliament (New Zealand)\n\n===Oakwood High School===\n\n* Aston Kelly, Actor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/dads-pride-over-his-bafta-award-winning-944989|title=Dad\u2019s pride over his BAFTA award-winning actor sons|last=News|first=Manchester Evening|date=2010-04-18|website=men|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n*[[David Joseph Henry]], Writer and human rights activist.\n*[[David Judge (actor)|David Judge]], Actor, playwright and performance poet.\n* [[Jason Manford]], Comedian, television and radio presenter.\n\n=== Wilbraham High School ===\n\n* [[David Threlfall]], English stage, film and television actor and director. [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)]].\n\n===Didsbury Technical High School===\n* [[Jim Cumbes]], cricketer and goalkeeper for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n* [[Paul Hart]], defender for Leeds United\n* [[Keith Newton (footballer)|Keith Newton]], defender for Blackburn Rovers and Burnley\n* Sir [[Michael Turner (businessman)|Michael Turner]] CBE FRAeS, Chief Executive from 2002 to 2008 of [[BAE Systems]], and chairman since 2008 of [[Babcock International]] and from 2012 of [[GKN]]\n\n===Chorlton Grammar School===\n* [[Frank Cohen]]\n*[[Trevor Davey]] (1926\u20132012), member of the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] ({{NZ election link year|1972}}\u20131975)<ref>{{cite book | page=95 | title=[[Who's Who in New Zealand]] | edition=11th | editor-first=James Edward | editor-last=Traue | date=1978 | publisher=Reed | location=Wellington}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Eccles (trade unionist)|Jack Eccles]]  CBE, President of the [[Trades Union Congress]] (1985-1986)\n* [[Roy Gibson]], Director General from 1985 to 1987 of the [[British National Space Centre]], and Director General from 1975 to 1980 of the [[European Space Agency]] (ESA)\n* [[John Gwynne (commentator)|John Gwynne]], darts commentator, father of [[Andrew Gwynne]], the Labour MP for [[Denton and Reddish (UK Parliament constituency)|Denton and Reddish]] since 2005\n* [[Harry Hargreaves (cartoonist)|Harry Hargreaves]], was an English cartoonist\n* [[Graham Paddon]], midfielder for [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n*[[Peter Barnes (footballer)|Peter Barnes]], Footballer and Sports Pundit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersB/BioBarnesPS.html|title=England Players - Peter Barnes|website=www.englandfootballonline.com|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Former staff ===\n*[[Adrian Henri]] \u2013 taught at the school during the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adrianhenri.com/biography-chronology-till1960.html|title=Adrian Henri: Biography, Chronology, 1932-1960|website=Adrianhenri.com|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\nGeorge McCloud brilliant physics teacher, parent of son based at CERN.\nMr Middleton, great lucid  mathematics teacher with son at Manchester University in Elec Eng\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/ School website]\n*[http://www.cgsob.co.uk Chorlton Grammar School Old Boys] (Unofficial alumni website)\n\n{{Schools in Manchester}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct grammar schools in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academies in Manchester]]\n[[Category:1924 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1924]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n| name         = Chorlton High School\n| image        = \n| image_size         = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.4365|-2.2649|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        = \n| established  = 1924\n| type         = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation     = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = Ms Z.  Morris<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cdn.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/sites/default/files/letters/Letter%20to%20parents%20-%20Y6.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425063244/http://cdn.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/sites/default/files/letters/Letter%20to%20parents%20-%20Y6.pdf |archive-date=25 April 2016 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| chair_label  = \n| chair        =\n| founder      = \n| address       = Nell Lane\n| city         = [[Manchester]]\n| county       = \n| country      = England\n| postcode     = M21 7SL\n| ofsted       = yes\n| dfeno        = 352/4281\n| urn          = 139148\n| staff        =\n| enrolment   = 1490~\n| gender       = [[Mixed-sex education|Coeducational]]\n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 16\n| houses       = \n| colours      =\n| publication  =\n| free_label_1 = Executive headteacher\n| free_1       = Mr A Park\n| free_label_2 =\n| free_2       =\n| free_label_3 =\n| free_3       =\n| website      = http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/\n}}\n'''Chorlton High School''' is a [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] secondary school with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], located in [[Chorlton-cum-Hardy]], Manchester, England. It has around 1500 pupils and 300 in each year.\n\n== History ==\n===Grammar school===\nChorlton Grammar School for Boys<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.manchester.gov.uk/Display.php?irn=61138&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&session=pass&QueryName=BasicQuery&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&Anywhere=SummaryData%7CAdmWebMetadata&QueryTerms=chorlton+school&QueryOption=Anywhere&StartAt=41&TestCookie=Test&__utmc=92605445&__utma=92605445.1656834395.1362681656.1362681656.1362681656.1&__utmz=92605445.1362681656.1.1.utmcsr%3Dmanchester.gov.uk%7Cutmccn%3D%28referral%29%7Cutmcmd%3Dreferral%7Cutmcct%3D%2Fa_to_z%2Fservice%2F1744%2Fimages_of_manchester&EMUSESSID=a3a5fefc82ca5a289274efa7f5a4a4cc|title=Chorlton Grammar School for Boys, Corkland Road, Chorlton-cum-Hardy, Manchester, 1927 |year=2010|work=Local Image Collection|publisher=Manchester City Council|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref> was founded in September 1924 with 110 boys due to the growing need to educate older local boys.<ref>An earlier school in Chorlton (founded) 1872) was renamed Chorlton High Schools in 1874; there was a Chorlton Grammar School in High Lane, 1896\u20131930. Lloyd, John (1972) ''The Township of Chorlton-cum-Hardy''. Manchester: E. J. Morten; pp. 98\u201399</ref> The first headmaster was A. F. Chappell, appointed in 1925. During Second World War it was twice evacuated to [[Fleetwood]], owing to the [[Manchester Blitz|Blitz]]; school records for the period during the war are sketchy, as the boys were moved around multiple times. The first headmaster retired in 1951 and was succeeded by Mr Merriman a year later. In 1952 it became a grammar school as pupil numbers started increasing again. The third and final headmaster was C. A. Crofts, appointed in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgsob.co.uk/cgsob/phpBB2/images/cgs/johnford/history.pdf|title=A Potted History|website=Cgsob.co.uk|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> There was at one time a lower school in Darley Avenue (formerly Barlow Hall School).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.manchester.gov.uk/Display.php?irn=64845&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&session=pass&QueryName=BasicQuery&QueryPage=%2Findex.php%3Fsession%3Dpass&Anywhere=SummaryData%7CAdmWebMetadata&QueryTerms=chorlton+school&QueryOption=Anywhere&StartAt=61&TestCookie=Test&__utmc=92605445&__utma=92605445.1656834395.1362681656.1362681656.1362698224.2&__utmz=92605445.1362681656.1.1.utmcsr%3Dmanchester.gov.uk%7Cutmccn%3D%28referral%29%7Cutmcmd%3Dreferral%7Cutmcct%3D%2Fa_to_z%2Fservice%2F1744%2Fimages_of_manchester&EMUSESSID=a3a5fefc82ca5a289274efa7f5a4a4cc&__utmb=92605445.2.10.1362698224|title=Chorlton High School, Darley Avenue (lower school), later Oakwood High School, lower school, Chorlton-cum-Hardy, Manchester, 1975|year=2010|work=Local Image Collection|publisher=Manchester City Council|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Comprehensive===\nDuring the 1960s it returned to its comprehensive roots. The existing building of Chorlton High School at Nell Lane (built in the early 1960s) replaced the old school at Sandy Lane (Corkland Road), which was formerly Chorlton Grammar School; in the early years it was called Oakwood High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.axcis.co.uk/schools-directory/Oakwood-High-School/34515|title=Oakwood High School|publisher=AXCIS Education Recruitment|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgsob.co.uk/cgsob/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=315|title=High school to Grammar school|last=Bancroft|first=Tom|date=2007\u20132010|work=Chorlton Grammar School Old Boys|accessdate=8 March 2013|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Chorlton Grammar School on Corkland Road merged with Barlow Hall Secondary Modern School in 1967, when all of Manchester's secondary state schools became comprehensive. Oakwood High School was the name give to the school, formed by the amalgamation of Wilbraham High School and Chorlton High School in the early 1980s. The current site of Chorlton High School at Nell Lane, was the original site of the Wilbraham High School Upper School.<ref>[https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/ever-present-head-retires-996026]{{cite news|title= Ever-present Head Retires Manchester Evening News, 27 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nIt was designated a specialist [[Arts College]] in 2002.<ref>[http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/artcollege_main.shtml Arts College] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129074052/http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/artcollege_main.shtml |date=29 January 2013 }}</ref> In May 2012, the school governors approved the controversial decision to convert into an [[Academy (England)|academy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Parents' anger over Chorlton High School academy 'whitewash'|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/parents-anger-over-chorlton-high-688824|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> The school became an academy on 1 January 2013.\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\nDue to the [[2020 coronavirus outbreak in the United Kingdom]], the school, along with all of the schools in the UK, was shut in March 2020 until further notice, leaving students into home learning.\n\n== Notable people ==\nA recording studio commemorates [[Maurice Gibb]], though none of the [[Bee Gees]] studied at Chorlton High School. They went to the nearby Oswald Road primary school but the family then emigrated to Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3705559.stm|title=Bee Gees go back to their roots|date=12 May 2004|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Chorlton High School ===\n* [[Tosin Adarabioyo]], footballer for Manchester City{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2020}}\n* [[U.S.G.|Geko]], rapper{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Trevor Davey]], Member of Parliament (New Zealand)\n\n===Oakwood High School===\n\n* Aston Kelly, Actor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/dads-pride-over-his-bafta-award-winning-944989|title=Dad\u2019s pride over his BAFTA award-winning actor sons|last=News|first=Manchester Evening|date=2010-04-18|website=men|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n*[[David Joseph Henry]], Writer and human rights activist.\n*[[David Judge (actor)|David Judge]], Actor, playwright and performance poet.\n* [[Jason Manford]], Comedian, television and radio presenter.\n\n=== Wilbraham High School ===\n\n* [[David Threlfall]], English stage, film and television actor and director. [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)]].\n\n===Didsbury Technical High School===\n* [[Jim Cumbes]], cricketer and goalkeeper for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n* [[Paul Hart]], defender for Leeds United\n* [[Keith Newton (footballer)|Keith Newton]], defender for Blackburn Rovers and Burnley\n* Sir [[Michael Turner (businessman)|Michael Turner]] CBE FRAeS, Chief Executive from 2002 to 2008 of [[BAE Systems]], and chairman since 2008 of [[Babcock International]] and from 2012 of [[GKN]]\n\n===Chorlton Grammar School===\n* [[Frank Cohen]]\n*[[Trevor Davey]] (1926\u20132012), member of the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] ({{NZ election link year|1972}}\u20131975)<ref>{{cite book | page=95 | title=[[Who's Who in New Zealand]] | edition=11th | editor-first=James Edward | editor-last=Traue | date=1978 | publisher=Reed | location=Wellington}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Eccles (trade unionist)|Jack Eccles]]  CBE, President of the [[Trades Union Congress]] (1985-1986)\n* [[Roy Gibson]], Director General from 1985 to 1987 of the [[British National Space Centre]], and Director General from 1975 to 1980 of the [[European Space Agency]] (ESA)\n* [[John Gwynne (commentator)|John Gwynne]], darts commentator, father of [[Andrew Gwynne]], the Labour MP for [[Denton and Reddish (UK Parliament constituency)|Denton and Reddish]] since 2005\n* [[Harry Hargreaves (cartoonist)|Harry Hargreaves]], was an English cartoonist\n* [[Graham Paddon]], midfielder for [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n*[[Peter Barnes (footballer)|Peter Barnes]], Footballer and Sports Pundit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersB/BioBarnesPS.html|title=England Players - Peter Barnes|website=www.englandfootballonline.com|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Former staff ===\n*[[Adrian Henri]] \u2013 taught at the school during the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adrianhenri.com/biography-chronology-till1960.html|title=Adrian Henri: Biography, Chronology, 1932-1960|website=Adrianhenri.com|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.chorltonhigh.manchester.sch.uk/ School website]\n*[http://www.cgsob.co.uk Chorlton Grammar School Old Boys] (Unofficial alumni website)\n\n{{Schools in Manchester}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct grammar schools in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academies in Manchester]]\n[[Category:1924 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1924]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:cb19:7d9:6b00:8541:f746:6d76:2dca", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFormer staff)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chorlton_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Adams Memorial", "text_new": "{{for|the statue in Rock Creek Cemetery|Adams Memorial (Saint-Gaudens)}}\n{{Infobox Protected area \n| name = Adams Memorial (proposed)\n| map = \n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| nearest_city = \n| area = \n| established = Proposed\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = Adams Memorial Foundation\n}}\nThe '''Adams Memorial''' is a proposed [[United States presidential memorial]] to honor the second [[President of the United States|President]] [[John Adams]]; his wife and prolific writer, [[Abigail Smith Adams|Abigail Adams]]; their son, the sixth President, [[John Quincy Adams]]; John Quincy Adams' wife, [[Louisa Catherine Adams]]; and other members of the [[Adams political family|Adams family]]. The memorial would also honor John Quincy Adam's son, [[Charles Francis Adams, Sr.]], a [[American civil war|Civil War]] diplomat, politician, and editor; and Charles' two sons, [[Henry Adams]], a noted historian and autobiographer, and academician [[Brooks Adams]].\n\nThe [[United States Congress]] authorized the Adams Memorial Foundation to proceed with the design and construction of a memorial on November 5, 2001.<ref name=\"Planned\">[http://parkplanning.nps.gov/showFile.cfm?projectID=44217&MIMEType=application%252Fmsword&filename=CWA%5Fmemorial%5Flaws%5F%5F%5Fbills%2Edoc&sfid=0 \"Memorial Legislation.\" National Capital Memorial Advisory Commission. June 22, 2013.] Accessed 2014-04-04.</ref> The foundation was authorized to raise private funds to construct a memorial on federal land in [[Washington, D.C.]] Once established, the memorial was then to be turned over to the federal government. On December 2, 2002, Congress amended this legislation to permit the Adams Memorial to be constructed within \"Area 1\", the central core of the District of Columbia centered on the [[National Mall]].<ref name=\"Planned\" />\n\nThe [[Commemorative Works Clarification and Revision Act]] of 2003 (CWCRA), however, gave the Adams Memorial Foundation and other memorial efforts then under way just seven years to raise the funds and begin construction. When the memorial foundation was unable to raise the funds, Congress passed legislation on October 30, 2009, giving the Adams Memorial effort until September 30, 2010, to complete its fundraising. On December 2, 2009, Congress passed legislation applying the CWCRA to the Adams Memorial, although the clock began running with passage of the Area I authorization. Congress extended the deadline for fund-raising yet again on May 24, 2010, giving the memorial until December 2, 2013, to finish its efforts.<ref name=\"StatusApril13\">[http://parkplanning.nps.gov/showFile.cfm?projectID=44217&MIMEType=application%252Fmsword&filename=Memorials%5FSunsets%5F%5F%5FCompletions%5F%284%2D15%2D13%29%2Edoc&sfid=0 \"Authorized Memorials - Status of Authorities.\" National Capital Memorial Advisory Commission. April 15, 2013.] Accessed 2014-04-04.</ref>\n\nAuthorization for the Adams Memorial expired on December 2, 2013, without a memorial having begun construction.<ref name=\"StatusApril13\" /> Congress again reauthorized the memorial on July 22, 2014, extending the deadline for an additional seven years, to December 2, 2020.<ref name=\"LynchBill\">[http://lynch.house.gov/press-release/house-passes-lynch-backed-reauthorization-adams-memorial-foundation \"House Passes Lynch-Backed Reauthorization of the Adams Memorial Foundation\" U.S. House of Representatives - Office of Congressman Stephen Lynch. July 22, 2014.] Accessed 2014-09-16.</ref> Following the continued failure of the foundation to select a location and raise funds,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/house-backs-plan-john-adams-memorial|title=House Backs Plan for John Adams Memorial|last=Tully-McManus|first=Katherine|date=2018-07-23|work=|language=en}}</ref> the 2019 [[John D. Dingell, Jr. Conservation, Management, and Recreation Act]] established an Adams Memorial Commission to establish the memorial, with members appointed by Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-by-the-president-29/|title=Statement by the President|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{USPL|107|62}}: Public Law 107-62, establishing the Foundation\n\n{{John Adams}}\n{{John Quincy Adams}}\n{{Washington DC landmarks|state=expanded}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Adams political family]]\n[[Category:Proposed buildings and structures in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the statue in Rock Creek Cemetery|Adams Memorial (Saint-Gaudens)}}\n{{Infobox Protected area \n| name = Adams Memorial (proposed)\n| map = \n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| nearest_city = \n| area = \n| established = Proposed\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = Adams Memorial Foundation\n}}\nThe '''Adams Memorial''' is a proposed [[United States presidential memorial]] to honor the second [[President of the United States|President]] [[John Adams]]; his wife and prolific writer, [[Abigail Smith Adams|Abigail Adams]]; their son, the sixth President, [[John Quincy Adams]]; John Quincy Adams' wife, [[Louisa Catherine Adams]]; and other members of the [[Adams political family|Adams family]]. The memorial would also honor John Quincy Adam's son, [[Charles Francis Adams, Sr.]], a [[American civil war|Civil War]] diplomat, politician, and editor; and Charles' two sons, [[Henry Adams]], a noted historian and autobiographer, and academician [[Brooks Adams]].\n\nThe [[United States Congress]] authorized the Adams Memorial Foundation to proceed with the design and construction of a memorial on November 5, 2001.<ref name=\"Planned\">[http://parkplanning.nps.gov/showFile.cfm?projectID=44217&MIMEType=application%252Fmsword&filename=CWA%5Fmemorial%5Flaws%5F%5F%5Fbills%2Edoc&sfid=0 \"Memorial Legislation.\" National Capital Memorial Advisory Commission. June 22, 2013.] Accessed 2014-04-04.</ref> The foundation was authorized to raise private funds to construct a memorial on federal land in [[Washington, D.C.]] Once established, the memorial was then to be turned over to the federal government. On December 2, 2002, Congress amended this legislation to permit the Adams Memorial to be constructed within \"Area 1\", the central core of the District of Columbia centered on the [[National Mall]].<ref name=\"Planned\" />\n\nThe [[Commemorative Works Clarification and Revision Act]] of 2003 (CWCRA), however, gave the Adams Memorial Foundation and other memorial efforts then under way just seven years to raise the funds and begin construction. When the memorial foundation was unable to raise the funds, Congress passed legislation on October 30, 2009, giving the Adams Memorial effort until September 30, 2010, to complete its fundraising. On December 2, 2009, Congress passed legislation applying the CWCRA to the Adams Memorial, although the clock began running with passage of the Area I authorization. Congress extended the deadline for fund-raising yet again on May 24, 2010, giving the memorial until December 2, 2013, to finish its efforts.<ref name=\"StatusApril13\">[http://parkplanning.nps.gov/showFile.cfm?projectID=44217&MIMEType=application%252Fmsword&filename=Memorials%5FSunsets%5F%5F%5FCompletions%5F%284%2D15%2D13%29%2Edoc&sfid=0 \"Authorized Memorials - Status of Authorities.\" National Capital Memorial Advisory Commission. April 15, 2013.] Accessed 2014-04-04.</ref>\n\nAuthorization for the Adams Memorial expired on December 2, 2013, without a memorial having begun construction.<ref name=\"StatusApril13\" /> Congress again reauthorized the memorial on July 22, 2014, extending the deadline for an additional seven years, to December 2, 2020.<ref name=\"LynchBill\">[http://lynch.house.gov/press-release/house-passes-lynch-backed-reauthorization-adams-memorial-foundation \"House Passes Lynch-Backed Reauthorization of the Adams Memorial Foundation\" U.S. House of Representatives - Office of Congressman Stephen Lynch. July 22, 2014.] Accessed 2014-09-16.</ref> Following the continued failure of the foundation to select a location and raise funds,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/house-backs-plan-john-adams-memorial|title=House Backs Plan for John Adams Memorial|last=Tully-McManus|first=Katherine|date=2018-07-23|work=|language=en}}</ref> the 2019 [[John D. Dingell, Jr. Conservation, Management, and Recreation Act]] established an Adams Memorial Commission to establish the memorial, with members appointed by Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-by-the-president-29/|title=Statement by the President|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{USPL|107|62}}: Public Law 107-62, establishing the Foundation\n\n{{John Adams}}\n{{John Quincy Adams}}\n{{Washington DC landmarks|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Adams political family]]\n[[Category:Proposed buildings and structures in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adams_Memorial"}
